<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-419-148  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 419 148.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Engineering Times  April 30 1990 n588 p37(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>The move to digital oscilloscopes accelerates.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Wittenberg, Roland C.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Sales of digital oscilloscopes surpassed analog scopes in 1989 forthe first time, a trend that is expected to accelerate.andP;  Digitaloscilloscopes are expected to account for almost three-quarters ofthe market by 1994, with the size of the market estimated to be$1.750 billion.andP;  Storage capability is the biggest reason forswitching to digital oscilloscopes.andP;  Storing waveform data indigital form means that measurements can be easily automated, datarapidly analyzed, displays of single-shot or intermittentwaveforms can be produced at high brightness levels along withrepetitive data, and hard copies of the information can beprinted.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     OscilloscopesTrendsMarket AnalysisMarket Share.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraphphotograph.andO;Caption:   Digital scopes will dominate worldwide sales. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>